  <scopecontent id="54495215eb4444244137da276b518cd1">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>Contains correspondence, memoranda, publications and subject files.</p><p>
Collection consists of more than one accession of Richard Magat office files ingested by the RAC over the years. An accession processed in 2018 consisted of a group of subject files regarding different press, publications, and public relations topics and was added to the end of the Subject Files series in order to reconstitute the relationship between the materials.</p><p>
The RAC holds another Ford Foundation, Office of Reports, Office Files of Richard Magat collection. A more deliberate collection arrangement appears to have been imposed on this set of material during processing. Therefore, it was decided not to integrate the 2018 accession with that collection or to merge the two collections together. The finding aid for FA728 of Ford Foundation, Office of Reports, Office Files of Richard Magat can be accessed <extref href="../FA728/overview">here</extref> .</p>  </scopecontent>
  <bioghist id="d06f6a3eb7a7173aaa8feee80f561ae8">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>The Ford Foundation was chartered by Henry and Edsel Ford in 1936 "to receive and administer funds for scientific, educational and charitable purposes, all for the public welfare", and initially served the Ford family's charitable interests in the Detroit area. Following the deaths of Edsel Ford (1943) and Henry Ford (1947), the Foundation was propelled to the forefront of philanthropy as the largest American foundation in terms of both endowment and yearly expenditures, and with an international scope to its major program areas. </p><p>
During the Foundation's first twenty years its major programs were in international economic development, primary and higher education, educational and public broadcasting, behavioral sciences, civil liberties, urban development, fine arts and the humanities. The Ford Foundation also partnered with the Rockefeller Foundation in supporting agricultural development in South America, Africa, and Southeast Asia. Since the 1970s, the Foundation has also pioneered programs in women's rights, energy policy, micro-financing in under-developed countries, establishing human rights groups, and improving international HIV/AIDS education. </p>  </bioghist>
  <bioghist id="9206b6bba122d056ea975478369ba6c6">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Richard Magat was a member of the Ford Foundation staff from 1957 until 1982. Throughout his career at the Foundation Mr. Magat worked in the Office of Reports. He held the following positions: </p><p>
April 1957, Writer </p><p>
October 1957, Program Assistant </p><p>
May 1958, Director </p><p>
March 1968, Director and Editor </p><p>
January 1982, Director (part time) </p><p>
As Director and Editor, Mr. Magat was responsible for: preparing press releases, writing notes to editors and drafting letters to congressmen; writing and editing Foundation publications and articles including the Annual Report, Current Interests, and Ford Foundation Letter; recommending public reports on Foundation activity; responding to media inquiries and arranging press conferences; and administering the Office of Reports.</p><p>
Mr. Magat also held the following positions:</p><p>
1947-51, Dayton Daily News, Ohio, The Binghamton Sun, New York, Reporter </p><p>
1951-52, McGraw-Hill Book Company, Editor in Technical Writing Service</p><p>
1952-53, Paramount News, Script Writer </p><p>
1953-57, New York University, Senior News Writer, Office of Information Services </p><p>
1967, Mayor's Advisory Panel on Decentralization of NYC Schools, Special Assistant </p><p>
1969, SUNY (Mount Vernon) Cooperative College, Instructor </p><p>
1975, Joint Committee for the Reappraisal of the Role of the Red Cross, Editor </p><p>
1979, SUNY (New York) Fashion Institute of Technology, Instructor </p><p>
Mr. Magat was born January 1, 1927. He received his A.B. degree in 1947 from New York University. Mr. Magat took additional courses at Columbia University, New York University and the New School. Mr. Magat is the author of Ford Foundation at Work, New York: Plenum (1979), and As Others See Us, Geneva: Henry Dumant Institute (1975). He also wrote articles for Saturday Review, Consumer Reports, Trans-action and other magazines and journals. Mr. Magat left the Ford Foundation in September 1982 to become President of the Edward W. Hazen Foundation. </p>  </bioghist>
